text:
This is from a piece I wrote 6 years ago after the murder of Michael Brown - Why Black Lives Should Matter to the Anti-Trafficking Movement. Don‚Äôt have new words right now. Black Lives Matter.

‚ÄúThe truth is that you can‚Äôt claim to be ‚Äòanti-trafficking‚Äô and not be anti-racism. Being anti-racist doesn‚Äôt just mean not saying the ‚Äòn‚Äô word or telling racist jokes. It means that you have to actively be engaged as an ally, question your own privilege and address all the subtle and not so subtle ways that structural racism interacts with your life.

You can‚Äôt say you care about trafficking victims of color, but not take a moment to understand how race impacts their lives. You can‚Äôt talk about prevention of commercial sexual exploitation without addressing poverty and how race and class are inextricably linked in this country. You can‚Äôt talk about options for survivors and ‚Äòaftercare‚Äô without acknowledging that those options look different for different survivors. You can‚Äôt sit quietly by on the sidelines because all this talk about race makes you uncomfortable. And you can‚Äôt pick and choose your social justice issues like you‚Äôre at a buffet bar.

All of this is linked, all of it is interconnected and all of this is indeed related to commercial sexual exploitation and trafficking, in all of its forms. As a movement with momentum and interest and a huge amount of support right now, we need to ensure that we‚Äôre a movement that is headed in the right direction on all issues of equality and justice, and we need to leverage that momentum to create real, lasting change. Black lives matter, and its past the time for the anti-trafficking movement to send that message loud and clear.‚Äù

#blacklivesmatter
#georgeflloydmatters
#breonnataylormatters
#ahmaudarberymatters
